The '''Bauzi''' or '''Baudi''' tribe consists of a group of 2,000 people<ref name="pg"/> living in the north-central part of the [[Indonesia]]n province of [[Papua (Indonesian province)|Papua]] (formerly [[Irian Jaya]]).  The Bauzi area consists of much of the west side of lower [[Mamberamo River]] area in northern Papua.<ref>{{cite book|author=Koninklijk Instituut voor Taal-, Land- en Volkenkunde|title=Excerpta Indonesica, Issues 25-34|year=1982|publisher=Centre for Documentation of Modern Indonesia, Royal Institute of Linguistics and Anthropology|isbn=|display-authors=etal}}</ref> The Bauzi people lived on hunting and gathering in the jungle.<ref>{{cite book|author=Michael C. Howard & Naffi Sanggenafa|title=Indigenous Peoples and Migrants of Northern Papua, Indonesia|year=2005|publisher=White Lotus Press|isbn=974-480-065-8}}</ref> While the Bauzi people were historically an [[animistic]] people group, they are now 65% [[Christian]].  For the most part, tribal warfare is no longer a large part of Bauzi culture and all Bauzi people speak the same language.  In recent years, linguists have been studying the language and translating various literature, including the [[Bible]], into the [[Bauzi language]].

