{{Infobox language family |name=Northwest Solomonic |region=[[Solomon Islands]] |familycolor=Austronesian |fam2=[[Malayo-Polynesian languages|Malayo-Polynesian]] |fam3=[[Oceanic languages|Oceanic]] |fam4=[[Western Oceanic languages|Western Oceanic]] |fam5=[[Meso-Melanesian languages|Meso-Melanesian]] |fam6=New Ireland – Northwest Solomonic |fam7=St George linkage |glotto=nort3225 |glottorefname=Northwest Solomonic }}
The family of '''Northwest Solomonic languages''' is a branch of the [[Oceanic languages]]. It includes the [[Austronesian languages]] of [[Bougainville Island|Bougainville]] and [[Buka Island|Buka]] in [[Papua New Guinea]], and of [[Choiseul Island|Choiseul]], [[New Georgia]], and [[Santa Isabel Island|Santa Isabel]] (excluding [[Bugotu language|Bugotu]]) in [[Solomon Islands]].
The unity of Northwest Solomonic and the number and composition of its subgroups, along with its relationship to other Oceanic groups, was established in pioneering work by [[Malcolm Ross (linguist)|Malcolm Ross]].<ref>See {{Harvtxt|Ross|1988}}.</ref>
==Components== [[File:Languages of Santa Isabel.png|thumb|Languages of Santa Isabel]] Northwest Solomonic languages group as follows:<ref>{{cite book | last = Lynch | first = John | authorlink = John Lynch (linguist) |author2=[[Malcolm Ross (linguist)|Malcolm Ross]] |author3=[[Terry Crowley (linguist)|Terry Crowley]] | year = 2002 | title = The Oceanic languages | location = Richmond, Surrey | publisher = Curzon | isbn = 978-0-7007-1128-4 | oclc = 48929366 }}</ref>
* Nehan – North Bougainville linkage **[[Nehan language|Nehan]] (Nissan) **'''Saposa–Tinputz''': [[Hahon language|Hahon]], [[Saposa language|Saposa]] (Taiof)–[[Teop language|Teop]], [[Tinputz language|Tinputz]] **'''Buka''': [[Halia language|Halia]]–[[Hakö language|Hakö]], [[Petats language|Petats]] **[[Papapana language|Papapana]] **[[Solos language|Solos]] * '''Piva–Bannoni''' family: [[Piva language|Piva]] (Lawunuia), [[Bannoni language|Bannoni]] * '''Mono–Uruavan''' family: [[Mono-Alu language|Mono-Alu]], [[Torau language|Torau]], [[Uruava language|Uruava]] *Choiseul linkage: [[Babatana language|Babatana]] (including Sisingga)–[[Ririo language|Ririo]], [[Vaghua language|Vaghua]]–[[Varisi language|Varisi]] *'''New Georgia – Ysabel''' family **[[New Georgia languages|New Georgia]] linkage: [[Simbo language|Simbo]] (Simbo Island), [[Roviana language|Roviana]]–[[Kusaghe language|Kusaghe]], [[Marovo language|Marovo]], [[Hoava language|Hoava]], [[Vangunu language|Vangunu]] ([[Vangunu Island]]), [[Nduke language|Nduke]] ([[Kolombangara Island]]), [[Ghanongga language|Ghanongga]] ([[Ranongga Island]]), [[Lungga language|Lungga]] ([[Ranongga Island]]), [[Ughele language|Ughele]] (North [[Rendova Island]]) **Ysabel linkage: [[Zabana language|Zabana]] (Kia)–[[Laghu language|Laghu]]<sup>†</sup>, [[Kokota language|Kokota]]–[[Zazao language|Zazao]] (Kilokaka)–[[Blablanga language|Blablanga]], [[Gao language|Gao]]–[[Cheke Holo language|Cheke Holo]] (Maringe, Hograno)
In addition, the extinct [[Kazukuru language]] was probably one of the New Georgia languages and [[Tetepare language|Tetepare]] may also have been one, if it was Austronesian at all.
