{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2012}}
{{Use Australian English|date=February 2012}}
{{Politics of Australia sidebar}}
'''Section 51(xxvi) of the Australian Constitution''',<ref name="s51(xxvi)">{{Cite Legislation AU|Cth|act|coaca430|Constitution|51}}(xxvi).</ref> commonly called "the race power", is the subsection of [[Section 51 of the Australian Constitution]] granting the Australian Commonwealth, the power to make special laws for people of any race.

As initially drafted, '''s 51(xxvi)''' empowered the [[Parliament of Australia|Parliament]] to make laws with respect to: "The people of any race, ''other than the [[Indigenous Australians|aboriginal]] race in any State'', for whom it is deemed necessary to make special laws". The Australian people voting at the [[Australian referendum, 1967 (Aboriginals)|1967 referendum]] deleted the words in italics.

[[Edmund Barton]] had argued in 1898 that s 51(xxvi) was necessary to enable the Commonwealth to "regulate the affairs of the people of coloured or inferior races who are in the Commonwealth".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://parlinfo.aph.gov.au/parlInfo/search/display/display.w3p;query=Id%3A%22constitution%2Fconventions%2F1898-1096%22 |title=Official Record of the Debates of the National Australasian Convention |location =Melbourne |date=27 January 1898 |pages=228–9}}</ref><ref name="French">{{cite book |last=French |first=Robert |author-link=Robert French |title=Australian Constitutional Landmarks |editor=H.P. Lee and George Winterton |publisher=Cambridge University Press |location=Cambridge UK |year=2003 |pages=180–212 |chapter=The Race Power: A Constitutional Chimera |isbn=0-521-83158-X}}</ref> The section was intended to enable the Commonwealth to pass laws restricting such migrant labourers such as the Chinese and [[Kanakas]]. Quick and Garran observed in 1901 that "It enables the Parliament to deal with the people of any alien race after they have entered the Commonwealth; to localise them within defined areas, to restrict their migration, to confine them to certain occupations, or to give them special protection and secure their return after a certain period to the country whence they came."<ref>{{cite book |last1=Quick |first1=J |author-link1=John Quick (politician) |last2=Garran |first2=R |author-link2=Robert Garran |title=The Annotated Constitution of the Australian Commonwealth |year=1901 |url=https://archive.org/stream/annotatedconstit00quicuoft#page/622/ |page=622}}</ref>

There were delegates, however, at the 1898 Convention who argued against the use of legislative power to deal specifically with alien races, accepting that people might be excluded from Australia based on race, but arguing that once people were admitted to the country they should be treated in the same way as other citizens.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://parlinfo.aph.gov.au/parlInfo/search/display/display.w3p;query=Id%3A%22constitution%2Fconventions%2F1898-1097%22 |title=Official Record of the Debates of the National Australasian Convention |location =Melbourne |date=28 January 1898}} [[Charles Kingston]] at pp. 244-7, [[John Quick (politician)|John Quick]] at pp, 245–6 and [[Josiah Symon]] at p. 250.</ref>

The scope of s 51(xxvi), is, subject to the Constitution itself, unfettered, in keeping with s 51 granting plenary powers to the Commonwealth.<ref>{{cite AustLII|HCA|22|1998|litigants=[[Kartinyeri v Commonwealth]] |parallelcite=(1998) 195 [[Commonwealth Law Reports|CLR]] 337 at p. 355 |courtname=auto}}.</ref> Section 51(xxvi) supports the rejection of legal equality requirements when considering legislation otherwise validly enacted under the Constitution.<ref>{{cite AustLII|HCA|27|1997|litigants=[[Kruger v Commonwealth]] |parallelcite=(1997) 190 [[Commonwealth Law Reports|CLR]] 1 }} at pp. 44-5 per Brennan CJ.</ref> Thus legislation empowered by other constitutional powers, such as in the [[Northern Territory National Emergency Response]],<ref>{{Cite Legislation AU|Cth|num_act|ntnera2007531|Northern Territory National Emergency Response Act}}.</ref> which was empowered by [[Section 122 of the Australian Constitution|section 122]],<ref name="s122">{{Cite Legislation AU|Cth|act|coaca430|Constitution|122}}.</ref> may be racially discriminatory.

In ''Kartinyeri v Commonwealth'', the High Court was split on whether s 51(xxvi) could be used to enact legislation that adversely discriminated on the basis of race. Justices [[William Gummow|Gummow]] and [[Kenneth Hayne|Hayne]] held that the use of race as the ais of parliamentary power was inherently discriminatory and that benefits to the people of one race may be detrimental to people of another.<ref>{{cite AustLII|HCA|22|1998|litigants=[[Kartinyeri v Commonwealth]] |parallelcite=(1998) 195 [[Commonwealth Law Reports|CLR]] 337 at [81]-[85] per Gummow and Hayne JJ |courtname=auto}}.</ref> [[Michael Kirby (judge)|Justice Kirby]] disagreed, holding that the race power did not permit the enactment of laws to the detriment of the people of any race.<ref>{{cite AustLII|HCA|22|1998|litigants=[[Kartinyeri v Commonwealth]] |parallelcite=(1998) 195 [[Commonwealth Law Reports|CLR]] 337 at [152] per Kirby J |courtname=auto}}.</ref> [[Mary Gaudron|Justice Gaudron]] held that it was difficult to conceive of circumstances in which a law to the disadvantage of a racial minority would be valid.<ref>{{cite AustLII|HCA|22|1998|litigants=[[Kartinyeri v Commonwealth]] |parallelcite=(1998) 195 [[Commonwealth Law Reports|CLR]] 337 at [44] per Gaudron J |courtname=auto}}.</ref>

In a report delivered to the Australian prime minister on 19 January 2012, it was recommended that a referendum be held for the repeal of s 51(xxvi), to be replaced by s 51A (which empowers the Commonwealth to make laws for Indigenous Australians, but also recognises Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islanders as Australia's first peoples) and s 116A (which prohibits racially discriminatory legislation or the making of laws under s51A that are not for the benefit of Indigenous peoples).<ref name="Panel">{{Citation|title=Recognising Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Peoples in the Constitution: Report of the Expert Panel |date=January 2012 |url=http://www.recognise.org.au/wp-content/uploads/shared/uploads/assets/3446_FaHCSIA_ICR_report_text_Bookmarked_PDF_12_Jan_v4.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150316172634/http://www.recognise.org.au/wp-content/uploads/shared/uploads/assets/3446_FaHCSIA_ICR_report_text_Bookmarked_PDF_12_Jan_v4.pdf |dead-url=no |archive-date=16 March 2015 |isbn=978-1-921975-29-5}}</ref>

