{{Infobox ethnic group| | group = Swiss-born people in France | image = | population = est. 200,730 (2017)<ref>https://www.diplomatie.gouv.fr/fr/dossiers-pays/suisse/presentation-de-la-suisse/</ref><ref name="auto">{{cite web|url=http://www.bfs.admin.ch/bfs/portal/fr/index/themen/01/02/blank/key/schweizer_im_ausland.html|title=Population|first=Office fédéral de la|last=statistique|website=Bfs.admin.ch|accessdate=28 August 2017}}</ref> | popplace = [[Île-de-France]], [[Aquitaine]], [[Languedoc-Roussillon]], [[Midi-Pyrénées]], [[Brittany]], [[Poitou-Charentes]], [[Corsica]], [[Centre-Val de Loire]] | langs = [[German language|German]], [[French language|French]], [[Italian language|Italian]], [[Romansh language|Romansh]] | rels = [[Swiss Reformed Church]], [[Eastern Orthodox Church|Orthodox]] and [[Catholicism]], | related = [[Swiss people|Swiss ]] }}
'''Swiss migration to France''' has resulted in [[France]] being home to one of the largest [[Swiss people|Swiss]]-born populations outside [[Switzerland]]. Migration from the Switzerland to France has increased rapidly from the 1980s onward and by 2013 there were an estimated 194,500<ref name="auto"/> Swiss citizens living in France.<ref name=Presentation>{{cite news|title=Présentation du Royaume-Uni|url=http://www.diplomatie.gouv.fr/fr/dossiers-pays/royaume-uni/presentation-du-royaume-uni|website=Diplomatie.gouv.fr|accessdate=28 August 2017}}</ref> Besides [[Paris]], the Swiss living in France have formed communities in southern France, Brittany, and Corsica.
